article.description: Rookie Dajuan Wagner scored 29 points to help the Cleveland Cavaliers snap their 15-game losing streak with a 111-101 victory over the Chicago Bulls on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Wagner's 29 propel Cavs to first win in 16 games

images.name: Wagner_Dajuan 021204 inline
images.caption: With 29 points, Dajuan Wagner tasted his first victory as a pro.

article.linkText: Cavs corral Bulls, end epic skid at 15 games
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- The atmosphere in Cleveland's locker room suggested they had just won a championship. It was only a 111-101 victory over the Chicago Bulls on Wednesday night, but snapping a 15-game losing streak was cause for celebration. "This is my first win as a pro and it feels great,'' rookie Dajuan Wagner said after tying his career-high with 29 points. "We got off this 15-game slide and have a chance to go on a different kind of streak,'' added rookie Carlos Boozer, who had a career-best 26 points. Ricky Davis also scored 26 as the Cavs won for the first time since a home-opening triumph over the NBA champion Los Angeles Lakers on Nov. 5. The streak was four shy of the franchise's worst single-season loss string, set at the end of the 1981-82 season. Jalen Rose scored 37 to lead the Bulls, who have lost eight straight and 14 of 16. "We don't have enough,'' Rose said. "You need seven or eight guys to come and produce every night.'' Cleveland's rookie duo missed all four of its shots in the fourth quarter as Chicago cut a 20-point deficit to four. "We probably did (celebrate a little early)'' Wagner admitted. "This is something we have to work on. We just can't let that happen.'' Rose sparked a 23-7 charge that brought the Bulls within 103-99 with 1:38 to play. Davis drove for a layup 17 seconds later and hit two free throws with 41 seconds left to make it 107-99. "We showed a lot of heart getting back into it, but we have a lot to learn,'' Bulls coach Bill Cartwright said. The announced attendance of 7,295 was the lowest for a Cleveland home game since Jan. 6, 1988, when 7,017 saw a victory over the Los Angeles Clippers. Davis returned from a two-game suspension by coach John Lucas for an on-court argument with teammate Tyrone Hill last Friday. Before the game, Davis addressed the issue for the first time and said his outburst came out of the frustration of losing. "I'm always going to get upset with losing and I'll probably have another outburst somewhere, but I know you can't disrespect teammates,'' Davis said. "I was just trying to be a team leader. I know we are all in this together. I just want to win.'' Afterward, Davis was ecstatic. "We can breathe again,'' he said. "The young guys played fantastic.'' Hill also returned after missing two games with a sprained left ankle. He had nine rebounds as Cleveland controlled the boards, 56-38. Wagner, a first-round pick who wears No. 2, scored 19 points and Boozer, the team's No. 2 pick who wears No. 1, added 14 in the first half. "Boozer was outstanding,'' Lucas said. "If he can have a night like this, this young in his career, it's going to make it hard to take him out of the lineup. And get used to what Juanny did. He's the real deal and will get the minutes to show what he can do.'' Wagner hit a 3-pointer to put the Cavs ahead to stay, 29-26. Boozer later scored eight consecutive Cleveland points as the Cavs extended their lead to 60-45 with a 22-12 run to close the half. "I think I have the two best rookies in the league,'' Lucas said. "Hopefully then can continue to work and get better.''

Game notes
Cavs G Bimbo Coles was sidelined with a left thigh contusion. "I don't expect him to play the next couple games,'' Lucas said, adding that F Darius Miles (left knee) and F-C Chris Mihm (left hamstring) "are coming along and we hope will play sometime this month.'' ... Chicago is 3-13 against the Cavs since 1998. ... Rose had 15 points in the third quarter.
